      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">An 11-year-old girl is brought to a clinic by her mother in a small town in India, with a history of intermittent diarrhea, periumbilical pain, and bloating that have persisted for the last three years. The symptoms occasionally exacerbate after the intake of milk and dairy products. On physical examination, rashes around the umbilicus are noted. A Benedict&#39;s test performed during the visit yields positive results, indicating the presence of reducing sugars in the urine. Given that an enzyme deficiency affecting lactose metabolism is suspected, which of the following food items is the girl most likely to tolerate?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8874372",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33034,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Yoghurt.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Lactose intolerance (lactose maldigestion) is a common <strong>cause of paediatric recurrent abdominal pain</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Lactase is a digestive enzyme located on the intestinal villi that converts the disaccharide lactose to the monosaccharides <strong>glucose and galactose.</strong> </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The monosaccharides can be absorbed across the intestinal epithelial cells. In an individual who has low intestinal lactase (lactose intolerance), the lactose cannot be broken down and passed into the lower intestine and colon. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The malabsorbed lactose can cause osmotic <strong>diarrhoea or be fermented by bacteria, resulting in pain, bloating and perianal rash.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Lactose intolerance can either be <strong>primary</strong> (lactase activity that gradually declines with aging) or <strong>secondary</strong> (an infection or enteropathy damages the villi, resulting in lactose intolerance).</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Many patients who have lactose intolerance diagnosed can tolerate <strong>Yoghurt.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Other products such as <strong>whole or skimmed milk, ice cream, or buttermilk have more lactose</strong> (approximately <strong>10 g/serving</strong>) and are less likely to be tolerated.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Whole milk:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Whole milk contains a <strong>significant amount of lactose </strong>and is therefore unlikely to be tolerated by someone with lactose intolerance.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Buttermilk:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Buttermilk generally contains <strong>less lactose than whole milk </strong>but still may contain enough to cause symptoms in someone with lactose intolerance.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Skimmed milk:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Skimmed milk contains a <strong>similar amount of lactose as whole milk </strong>and is therefore unlikely to be tolerated by someone with lactose intolerance.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Yoghurt</strong>, is the <strong>most likely food that will be tolerated due to its lower lactose content </strong>compared to <strong>whole milk </strong>and <strong>skimmed milk</strong>, making it a suitable alternative for individuals with lactose intolerance.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No 1854-1874. </span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">O P Ghai &ndash; Page No-293</span></span></strong></p>",
